<div class="post"><div class="posttop"><div class="username">Hachi Go</div><div class="date">01-04-2008, 10:29 AM</div></div><div class="posttext">I'm not surprised with the way the voting went in Iowa.  I went to a couple of Obama events in Illinois, and they were hitting Iowa hard with volunteers.  With such close proximity to Illinois, Obama had a very good shot of winning (Which he eventually did).<br />
 <br />
New Hampshire is a very different story though.  If Obama wins NH, then you can kiss the Democratic race goodbye for Edwards, Hillary and the rest of the Democratic candidates.<br />
 <br />
As for the Republican side, I was surprised to see Giuliani lose so much ground.  He should also do a lot better in NH but he's candidacy is all but done with the Iowa results...<br />
<br />
Personally, I don't care much for Giuliani.  However, as I stated earlier Iowa's caucuses and New Hampshire's primaries are an innaccurate gauge of predicting the party's nomination.<br />
<br />
For example, in 1992, Bill Clinton lost both Iowa and New Hampshire, that sure did turn out to be a good indicator of who would win (sarcasm).  In  1996 the primaries were basically irrevalent for the Democrats due to Clinton being the incumbent.  2000 was also basically irrevalent for the Democrats with only Al Gore and Bill Bradley being front runners in the primaries, making Al Gore nearly uncontested for the race.  2004 was the only year since in which John Edwards and John Kerry kept &quot;trading ground&quot;.  Even going back to 1988, Michael Dukakis lost Iowa and won New Hampshire.  <br />
<br />
Just evidence that media hypes the Iowa causus and NH primary too much.</div></div><hr />


