<div class="post"><div class="posttop"><div class="username">Eleden</div><div class="date">01-07-2008, 01:07 AM</div></div><div class="posttext">And when was the last time that the peoples vote mattered?  Last time I checked the Electoral College votes in the president. <br />
<br />
Ohio is a republican state. If every single person votes democratic in Ohio, the electoral college can and 9 times out of 10 will vote republican, because republicans run the electoral college here in Ohio. Same goes for all states. Whatever the party of the electoral college is of your state, thats what it votes regardless of of popular vote.<br />
<br />
I just use voting to get out of work mainly.<br />
<br />
Ohio is not a Republican state.  It's what many pundits like to call a &quot;purple&quot; state.  There's generally an even number of Democratic and Republican voters, with a large independent block.  Republicans also do not run the electoral college in Ohio.   I'm not sure you're fully understanding how our system works.  We elect a new slate of electors every year that are pledged to a particular candidate.  If the state votes Democrat then the Democrats will get their own group of electoral voters, if the GOP wins Ohio then the opposite occurs.</div></div><hr />


