<div class="post"><div class="posttop"><div class="username">Hachi Go</div><div class="date">01-07-2008, 12:19 PM</div></div><div class="posttext">So I had some facts screwed up, but the one that remains is that the popular vote is not what matters. Even though the people vote more for one, even across the country, it still depends on the amount of votes from the electoral college. Which is crap<br />
<br />
The popular vote does matter.... Popular vote in a particular state is what determines the voting power of that state's delegates to the Electoral College.<br />
<br />
I.E.:  Ohio has 20 Electors, those electors get there by means of whichever candidate wins the state.  It's a representative group of the winner of the state. <br />
<br />
You have to keep in mind that we are a Republic, where we elect &quot;X&quot; number of individuals  where &quot;X&quot; equals a portion of the population of a state.  We are not the commonly misconceived Democracy that the majority of Americans assume we are.<br />
<br />
On the Electoral College......Except for 2 times in our 232 year history where we've had 54 presidential elections, making the Electoral College accurate 96.23% of the time. I'm not justifying the Electoral College nor am I condoning it but i will say this.... it's our our system and for the most part it's been right in coinciding with the popular vote to determine the next president</div></div><hr />


