<div class="post"><div class="posttop"><div class="username">Eleden</div><div class="date">01-07-2008, 05:05 PM</div></div><div class="posttext">On the Electoral College......Except for 2 times in our 232 year history where we've had 54 presidential elections, making the Electoral College accurate 96.23% of the time. I'm not justifying the Electoral College nor am I condoning it but i will say this.... it's our our system and for the most part it's been right in coinciding with the popular vote to determine the next president<br />
<br />
Wrong.  It's actually happened four times. <br />
<br />
Election of 1824: Andrew Jackson wins popular vote but still loses.<br />
Election of 1876: Samuel Tilden wins popular vote by moderate margin but loses electoral college by one.<br />
Election of 1888: Grover Cleveland loses his reelection bid, but wins the popular vote.<br />
Election of 2000: Al Gore wins the popular vote, but loses the electoral college due to SCOTUS intervention.<br />
<br />
Personally I think it's high time we abolish the electoral college.  It was created because the founding fathers were worried we wouldn't know enough about a candidate before we elected him.  With the spread of cable news and the quick transfer of information, I think it's safe to say Americans will probably be informed enough to not elect a tyrant....<br />
<br />
Of course I could be wrong... we elected Bush after all.<br />
<br />
<br />
A lot of states are considering amending their state constitutions regarding the electoral college.  Their electoral votes will be awarded to the candidate that wins the popular vote at a national level.</div></div><hr />


